          "settings": {
            "image": "shopify:\/\/shop_images\/history.jpg",
            "title": "",
            "text": "<p>This Bob's® restaurant was built in 1949 by local residents <strong>Scott MacDonald<\/strong> and <strong>Ward Albert<\/strong>, and is the oldest remaining Bob’s Big Boy® in America.<\/p><p>It was designed by renowned architect <a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/architecture\">Wayne McAllister<\/a>, incorporating the 1940's transitional design of streamline modern style while anticipating the free-form 50's coffee shop architecture.<\/p><p>The towering Bob's® sign is an integral part of the building design and its most prominent feature. The restaurant was honored, receiving the designation as a <a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/conservancy\">\"Point of Historical Interest\"<\/a> by the state of California.<\/p><p><\/p>"
          }
        },
        "column2": {
          "type": "column",
          "settings": {
            "title": "MORE HISTORY",
            "text": "<p><a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/opening\">The Big Boy® Story<\/a><\/p><p><a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/architecture\">Architecture of Wayne McAllister<\/a><\/p><p><a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/beatles\">The Beatles Booth<\/a><\/p><p><a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/history\/heat\">Filming Michael Mann's <em>Heat<\/em><\/a><\/p><p><\/p><p>The current owner, the MacDonald Family, acquired control of the restaurant in 1993 and began to restore it to its past glory.<\/p><p>An exterior patio was added; the tower sign was rehabilitated; the dining room was remodeled; \"Car Hop\" service was re-introduced on Saturday and Sunday nights; and on Friday nights a <a href=\"https:\/\/bobs.net\/events\/classic-car-show\">“Classic Car Show”<\/a> reverberates in the parking lot.<\/p><p><\/p><p>Many resources were spent to restore the quality of food, service, and hospitality which made Bob's® a tradition and your meal the very best value in Southern California.<\/p><p><strong>“The Bob's Big Boy<\/strong>®<strong> and sign ensemble is significant to the history, culture, and architecture of Los Angeles and merits recognition and preservation.”<\/strong><\/p><p><strong>Barbara A. Hoff<\/strong> of the LA Conservancy<\/p><p><\/p>"
          }
        },
